social_posts.post_text: I grow more fond of the 300SL every day

This is a Porsche powered Mclaren F1 car from the 1980's turbo era. Back in the day, these cars had tiny V6's with turbos bigger than your head, often making more power than they weighed during qualifying runs. This is by far my favorite thing I got to witness at @velocityinvitational as Mika Hakkinen tore up Laguna Seca, making that turbo really scream.

This is the C3 Corvette's magnum opus. The L88 package consisted of a seven liter V8 that made roughly 500 horsepower, heavy duty racing suspension and some small weight savings. Only 20 cars left the factory with this option, and about 10 are believed to exist today. I'm led to believe this is a legitimate example with the center console plaque that has the model designation "L88" engraved into it as well as the hood decals, but the only way to truly tell is to rip the car apart and look for the gas tank sticker.
950 screaming red horses in Newport Beach

The Porsche 959SC, beautifully and meticulously restored by the geniuses at @canepamotorsport and now making a hair over 800 horsepower, a good bit more oomph than the stock 450 wheel HP. In the 80's, MSRP was around $300,000 for one of these. Nowadays, and especially for this specific 959, you would need to add another comma and another zero to that original price.
4 screaming wankels stacked front to back, variable length intake runners, and the ability to exceed 10,000 RPM, all wrapped up in a white and blue 3 piece suit. There is nothing like a Mazda 787
There is no Ferrari quite like the F40

Pore over the unique details that make an American Le Mans dominant LMP2 machine, crafted by none other than Porsche: the almighty RS Spyder. Notable drivers such as Patrick Long, Andy Wallace and Jos Verstappen piloted the RS Spyder from 2005-2010 to a multitude of race victories both in the US and abroad. This car in particular is an RS Spyder EVO, which was a refresh that supplied a ~25 horsepower bump and changed the look of the car significantly in 2007. The 3.4 liter V8 which spun to nearly 11K RPM would later be stroked out and tuned for road use in the 918 Spyder, and further developed to handle boost with the new 963 GTP car, marking Porsche's return to top level IMSA racing. TL:DR, its badass, and I would have killed to see this thing run around the track it debuted on

After being converted to a 935 post-ban, this chassis was restored to its former glory and later sold at Amelia Island in 2022 for a whopping $912,500

Behold the 1000 Horsepower, all wheel drive, sequential transmission equipped, ground effect utilizing go kart with body panels, known more formally as Rod Millen's "Toyota Tacoma". It really doesnt take a whole lot of observation to figure why this car won back to back Pikes Peak Hillclimbs in 1998 and 1999, from the undoubtably enormous driver mod to the wing which looks big enough to comfortably sleep on. I got to see this beast run last year for the 100 year anniversary of the climb, but I wasn't able to get close enough to take in the little details, let alone to photograph this beast. This set of photos is my retribution.

Camping at Laguna Seca was such a special experience to me, especially when I woke up early and got to waltz around the paddock with nearly 0 people around. On one of these morning walks, I stumbled upon the mighty Porsche 917PA, and it was one of the top cars I wanted to see and photograph this year. Known for being Porsche's first flat-12 foray into Can-Am in 1969, it entered the series roughly halfway through the season, yet still managed to secure 4th place in the championship. This of course drove Porsche to keep racing in Can-Am, thus putting on outright-dominant performances with the likes of the twin-turbocharged 917/10 and the even more powerful 917/30, known for dominating Can-Am until the series dissolved in 1974 due to financial issues and a certain oil crisis in the USA.

Back in the mid-1960's, Ferrari had the 275, Chevrolet had the Corvette, and Porsche had the 911. Feeling left out, Toyota decided they needed a sports car as well, and with the help from Yamaha, they made the beautiful 2000GT. Taking exterior design cues from the Jaguar E-Type and suspension geometry inspiration from the Lotus Elan, as well as a souped up, DOHC variant of the 2 Liter engine from the Toyota Crown, Toyota and Yamaha proved they could craft a truly sensational drivers car, and they continue to do so today
An assortment of the epic machines of group 6 from the Rolex Reunion. Always one of my favorite groups to watch, especially when the 935's are shooting flames
Hanging with the homies, hovering around a homologation special. This 190E Evo II is one of if not my single favorite Mercedes-Benz of all time

Behold, the only photos I got on 17 Mile Drive this year. Fortunately for me, the subject is one of my favorite Porsche's ever manufactured, a delightful 996 GT3RS parked up for the Pebble Beach coast during the Concours. There are only ~682 of these beauties, and you could only option them in white with either red or blue accents. Having only seen a red accented RS in the past, I hollered

This Porsche 962, specifically chassis 139, went up for auction last year during car week, where it fetched a sizable bag of 1.4 Million Bucks. Up until car week 2023, I had assumed this car would go into hiding, not to be seen by the light of day until a sale or auction in the distant future. Much to my utter delight, here are my photos (and a few video clips) of 139 at the 2023 Rolex Reunion, both in the paddock and being driven in anger (peep the 3 wheeling through turn 2!)

Celebrating Wankel Wednesday with @mazdamotorsports GORGEOUS RX792P catching some sun at the @japaneseclassiccarshow in Long Beach this year. A very promising chassis which had a subpar run in its debut season in 1992, with a best finish of 2nd at Watkins Glen, of course behind the championship winning Gurney Toyota Eagle MKIII. A few fire issues and mediocre finishes later would cap off Mazda's 92' campaign, but it only got worse for the 792P as a regulation change loomed on the horizon for the GTP class. IMSA wanted to move away from the 11 year old GTP program and shift focus to open-top prototypes, and Mazda Japan, whom supplied the 4 rotor engines, saw this news and pulled the plug on the RX792 and Mazda's GTP dreams. The 1993 IMSA GTP season would go on to be dominated by Dan Gurney's Toyotas, winning 10 of the 11 races that year. But I think if Mazda had more time to develop and perfect the RX792P, we could have seen some different results to the swan song season of GTP in 1993.
